        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# From Pretraining to Prompting {#sec-intro}\n",
        "\n",
        "In Module 4 Lecture 1 we saw how transformers are *pretrained*: masked language modeling\n",
        "(BERT), causal language modeling (GPT), and span corruption (T5) teach a model to represent\n",
        "language deeply from raw text. Pretraining produces a powerful general-purpose encoder or\n",
        "decoder — but a general-purpose model still needs to be aimed at a specific task.\n",
        "\n",
        "This lecture covers the full spectrum of **adaptation strategies**:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Strategy | Cost | Data needed | Suited for |\n",
        "|----------|------|-------------|------------|\n",
        "| Prompt engineering | Zero compute | Zero labels | Rapid prototyping, task spec |\n",
        "| Few-shot prompting | Zero compute | 3–10 examples | Low-data settings |\n",
        "| Instruction tuning | Medium | 10k–1M examples | Multi-task generalization |\n",
        "| RLHF / DPO | High | Human preference pairs | Alignment, safety |\n",
        "| Full fine-tuning | High | 1k–100k labels | Max accuracy, domain shift |\n",
        "| LoRA / Adapters | Low | 1k–100k labels | VRAM-constrained adaptation |\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# The Shift to Prompt-Based Approaches\n",
        "\n",
        "## From Training-Centric to Inference-Centric AI\n",
        "\n",
        "For most of ML history, behavior was determined at **training**. Once deployed, a model was frozen: changing behavior required retraining. LLMs shatter this assumption. Their behavior is no longer fixed at deployment — it can be **steered at inference time** through prompts, context, and task specifications.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the **Pre-train, Prompt, and Predict** paradigm [@liu2023pretrain]:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Pretrain**: learn a general language model on a massive unlabelled corpus.\n",
        "- **Prompt**: supply a natural-language template that converts the downstream task into a language modeling problem.\n",
        "- **Predict**: let the model fill in the blanks — no gradient updates required.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Formal Notation\n",
        "\n",
        "Given:\n",
        "- $x$ — original input (e.g., a sentence)\n",
        "- $f_{\\text{prompt}}(x)$ — a **prompting function** that converts $x$ into a prompted input $x'$ (fills in a template around $x$)\n",
        "- $x'$ — the prompted input (template + input)\n",
        "- $z$ — the **answer** (filled slot, e.g., a class label, a word, or a generated span)\n",
        "- $f_{\\text{fill}}(x', z)$ — the **answer search** function that scores candidate answers $z$\n",
        "\n",
        "The prediction is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align}\n",
        "\\hat{z} = \\arg\\max_{z \\in \\mathcal{Z}} \\, P(f_{\\text{fill}}(x', z) \\mid \\theta)\n",
        "\\end{align}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\mathcal{Z}$ is the set of candidate answers and $\\theta$ are the (frozen) model parameters.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example** — sentiment classification:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Step | Text |\n",
        "|------|------|\n",
        "| Input $x$ | \"The quarterly earnings exceeded expectations.\" |\n",
        "| Template | \"[X] The sentiment of this text is [Z].\" |\n",
        "| Prompted $x'$ | \"The quarterly earnings exceeded expectations. The sentiment of this text is ___\" |\n",
        "| Answer space $\\mathcal{Z}$ | {\"positive\", \"negative\", \"neutral\"} |\n",
        "| Prediction $\\hat{z}$ | \"positive\" (highest log-prob under the LM) |\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Classical Learning vs. Generative Conditioning\n",
        "\n",
        "### Classical Supervised Learning\n",
        "\n",
        "In the classical paradigm:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align}\n",
        "y = f_\\theta(x)\n",
        "\\end{align}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$\\theta$ encodes all learned behavior. Changing the model's behavior requires modifying $\\theta$.\n",
        "This creates a rigid workflow: expensive offline training followed by static, brittle deployment.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Generative Conditioning\n",
        "\n",
        "Generative models define a conditional distribution:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align}\n",
        "P(Y \\mid X, \\theta)\n",
        "\\end{align}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Adding a prompt $p$ at inference time adds a third control variable:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{align}\n",
        "P(Y \\mid X, p, \\theta)\n",
        "\\end{align}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Prompts act as *soft constraints*: they reshape the model's posterior distribution without touching the weights.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Prompt as an Inference-Time Control Signal\n",
        "\n",
        "A prompt functions as a **control interface** for a probabilistic model:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Conditioning signal** — narrows the space of plausible outputs (Bayesian analogy).\n",
        "- **Soft constraint** — biases trajectories probabilistically, not deterministically.\n",
        "- **Semantic policy** — encodes how the model should behave (\"Be concise\", \"Act as a SQL expert\").\n",
        "- **Steering mechanism** — alters token likelihoods to enable rapid task adaptation without retraining.\n",
        "\n",
        "```{dot}\n",
        "digraph InferenceConditioning {\n",
        "    rankdir=TB;\n",
        "    node [shape=rectangle, style=rounded, fontsize=12];\n",
        "    subgraph cluster_input {\n",
        "        label=\"Inputs\";\n",
        "        style=dashed;\n",
        "        X [label=\"User Input\\nX\"];\n",
        "        P [label=\"Prompt / Context\\np\"];\n",
        "    }\n",
        "    Theta [label=\"Model Parameters\\nθ (frozen)\", shape=rectangle, style=\"rounded,filled\", fillcolor=lightgray];\n",
        "    subgraph cluster_inference {\n",
        "        label=\"Inference Process\";\n",
        "        style=dashed;\n",
        "        Combine [label=\"Conditioning:\\n[X, p]\"];\n",
        "        LM [label=\"Generative Model\\nP(Y | X, p, θ)\"];\n",
        "    }\n",
        "    Y [label=\"Output Distribution\\nY\"];\n",
        "    X -> Combine;\n",
        "    P -> Combine;\n",
        "    Theta -> LM;\n",
        "    Combine -> LM;\n",
        "    LM -> Y;\n",
        "}\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Prompt Engineering, Fine-Tuning, and RAG: A Comparative View\n",
        "\n",
        "![Venn Diagram of Prompt Engineering, Fine-tuning, and RAG](../M3/M03_lecture01_figures/Prompt_Engineering_vs_RAG-tuning_Venn_Diagram.jpg){width=60% fig-align=center fig-alt=\"Venn diagram showing the relationship between prompt engineering, fine-tuning, and RAG\" #fig-venn-diagram}\n",
        "\n",
        "| Approach | Weight Update | Data Required | Iteration Speed | Best For |\n",
        "|----------|:---:|---|---|---|\n",
        "| **Prompt Engineering** | None | 0 labels | Minutes | Task spec, style control |\n",
        "| **Fine-Tuning** | Yes — all | Labeled examples | Hours–days | Domain adaptation, new skills |\n",
        "| **RAG** | None | Document corpus | Minutes | Factual accuracy, recency |\n",
        "| **LoRA / PEFT** | Yes — subset | Labeled examples | Hours | VRAM-limited adaptation |\n",
        "\n",
        "They interact: **Prompting + RAG** = reasoning over external knowledge; **Prompting + Fine-tuning** = stable specialized behavior; **RAG + Fine-tuning** = domain-specific grounding.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Worked Example: How a Prompt Reshapes Token Probabilities\n",
        "\n",
        "### Without a Prompt\n",
        "\n",
        "Input: `\"Complete the sentence: The cat\"`\n",
        "\n",
        "The model's next-token distribution (pretrained priors):\n",
        "\n",
        "| Token | Probability |\n",
        "|:-------|:-------------:|\n",
        "| runs  | 0.40 |\n",
        "| sleeps | 0.35 |\n",
        "| . | 0.15 |\n",
        "| dog | 0.05 |\n",
        "| cat | 0.05 |\n",
        "\n",
        "### With a Dramatic-Scene Prompt\n",
        "\n",
        "Prompt: `\"Write a dramatic action scene. Complete the sentence: The cat\"`\n",
        "\n",
        "| Token | Probability |\n",
        "|:-------|:-------------:|\n",
        "| runs | 0.55 |\n",
        "| leaps | 0.25 |\n",
        "| attacks | 0.10 |\n",
        "| sleeps | 0.03 |\n",
        "| . | 0.02 |\n",
        "\n",
        "\"sleeps\" collapses 0.35 → 0.03. No weights changed — only the **conditioning context**.\n",
        "\n",
        "### With a Role + Style Prompt\n",
        "\n",
        "Prompt: `\"You are a veterinarian writing a calm, factual report. Complete the sentence: The cat\"`\n",
        "\n",
        "| Token | Probability |\n",
        "|:-------|:-------------:|\n",
        "| sleeps | 0.50 |\n",
        "| rests | 0.20 |\n",
        "| is | 0.15 |\n",
        "| runs | 0.05 |\n",
        "| . | 0.05 |\n",
        "\n",
        "The prompt now acts as a **semantic policy** — \"calm, factual\" shifts the distribution toward clinical, low-emotion verbs.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Training Settings: Zero-Shot, Few-Shot, Full-Data\n",
        "\n",
        "The prompting framework naturally accommodates different data regimes [@liu2023pretrain]:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Setting | Labeled examples | Parameter update? | Notes |\n",
        "|---------|:---:|:---:|---|\n",
        "| **Zero-shot** | 0 | No | Model infers task from the template alone |\n",
        "| **Few-shot (in-context)** | 1–10 | No | Examples in the prompt context window |\n",
        "| **Full-data supervised** | 1k–100k | Yes (fine-tune) | Standard supervised learning on top of pretrained features |\n",
        "\n",
        "In-context few-shot is a distinguishing *emergent ability* of large models: GPT-3 (175B) can solve new tasks from 3 examples; GPT-2 (1.5B) largely cannot.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Prompting Patterns: Code Demonstrations\n",
        "\n",
        "## Zero-Shot vs Few-Shot Prompt Construction\n",
        "\n",
        "These cells demonstrate prompt formatting patterns in pure Python — no API key required.\n",
        "The patterns translate directly to any LLM API (OpenAI, Anthropic, HuggingFace)."
      ],
